Most of this code is taken/modified from https://github.com/F0bes/gs4ps2qt and https://github.com/F0bes/gs4ps2.

To use you should have a way of running ELF files from a USB drive, such as FreeMCBoot with ulaunchELF. Then use the follownig steps:
1. Compile the "runner-usb.elf" and copy it to the root directory of the USB drive.
2. Copy an extracted GS dump (i.e. ".gs" extension) to the same directory.
3. Create a config file (decribed below) named "gs-dump-runner-2.txt" in the same directory.
4. Run "runner-usb.elf" and wait until the screen turns fully green, which means the frame is dumped.

Important: the GS dump file must be small enough to fit in the PS2 main memory, so less than 32 MB.

Config file example:
```
mode: vsync
num: 2
bwpx: 512
psm: PSM_32
block: 0x0
x: 0
y: 0
width: 512
height: 448
filename_dump: sotc-moon.gs
filename_save: sotc-moon-frame-2.bmp
```
- `mode: vsync`: dump counting by frames (the other option is `packets`).
- `num: 2`: dump the second frame (or second packet if `mode: packets`).
- `bwpx: 512`: buffer width to dump in pixels (usually same as the frame width).
- `psm: PSM_32`: frame is `PSM_32` format. The options are `PSM_32`, `PSM_24`, `PSM_16`, `PSM_16S`, `PSMZ_32`, `PSMZ_24`, `PSMZ_16`, `PSMZ_16S`.
- `block: 0x0`: block address of the frame. This must be obtained by e.g. dumping the frames in PCSX2.
- `x: 0`: x offset of the frame in the buffer is `0` (`0` is almost always what you want).
- `y: 0`: y offset of the frame in the buffer is `0` (`0` is almost always what you want).
- `width: 512`: width of the frame in pixels (usually same as the buffer width).
- `height: 448`: height of the frame in pixels.
- `filename_dump: sotc-moon.gs`: name of the GS dump file on the USB.
- `filename_save: sotc-moon-frame-2.bmp`: name of the file to save the frame to. Only outputs bmp format.
